Obviously not. The monster just roared and tried to charge directly at Sasalin. Thank goodness, although Sasalin was huge, he was still quite agile and managed to dodge in time. However, Nisi couldn't help but scream and almost slipped off Sasalin's smooth scales.
"How can we kill them?" Nisi shouted.
"Aim for their heads!"
"This is too hard!"
Sasalin roared, circled around, and flew toward the mountain he called home. The black monster followed closely behind, but when it was attacked from behind by fire, it became somewhat panicked. The monster had yet to realize it had gained another opponent. Sasalin slowed down, then struck the monster's head fiercely with his tail, knocking it off course, and the monster became even more panicked.
The monster roared, hissing from its throat as it flew straight upward, continuously spitting something into the air. Suddenly, everything around them turned pitch black, as if the monster were absorbing the light from the sky and replacing it with an eternal darkness.
Sasalin went momentarily blind and tried to back away, but found himself colliding with the tree branches and falling to the ground below. The monster apparently knew exactly where Sasalin had fallen and flew straight toward him, taking the cloud of darkness with it.
"Kayer!" Tenuk shouted, flying out of the cloud and beginning to circle, trying to find Nisi and Sasalin in the darkness below. "What should we do, Kayer...? Kayer, where are you?"
Nisi struggled to her feet. She felt sure she had broken bones, but her strange, unnatural self-healing ability had already begun to take effect. Sasalin was not in the same condition; he lay helplessly on the ground, leaning against a tree he had crushed. Nisi tried to walk toward Sasalin, but she could barely see anything due to the darkness around her. Terrifying shadows surrounded her, and something was screeching within them.
A terrible club-like tail smashed down violently onto the ground, knocking Nisi off her feet. She noticed the tail was swinging wildly, but its target apparently wasn't her. Nisi barely saw the monster roaring and frantically scratching at the shadows it had created with its claws. Something was teleporting through the darkness, waiting for an opportunity to strike the monster.
Suddenly, a gunshot shattered the air, and the monster immediately fell silent, collapsing motionless to the ground. The surrounding darkness dissipated, revealing the truth. Kayer stood on the monster's corpse, holding a rifle, panting heavily.
"That was... one of the weirdest shadow jumps I've ever done... Tanto Katelorn..." Kayer gasped. Somehow, his eyes glowed with black light, and a dark energy surged within him. But as Kayer spoke, his organic armor regained its color, and his eyes returned to their normal yellow.
After a while, Nisi finally realized what had happened. They all knew that Kayer possessed strange shadow abilities, but he rarely used them because most people believed such power was extremely evil and terrifying. However, Nisi didn't know that Kayer could use this ability in any darkness. Moreover, from Kayer's reaction, it seemed that even he himself was quite surprised.
"Are you okay?" Nisi couldn't help but ask.
"I'm fine. I killed that thing, and I'll be back to normal soon." Kayer looked at his "masterpiece," when Tenuk landed beside him, transforming back into his original Spast form.
Now, the monster was motionless, and they could take a good look at what it really was. Its skin was jet black and glossy, covered with a slimy liquid that clung tightly to its body. It had four wings and four legs, each ending in long, slender claws, and two straight horns grew from its skull.
Tenuk and Kayer hadn't even had time to figure out what kind of creature it was when a monster screeched and leaped out from the nearby bushes. At that moment, a familiar car crashed into the side of the monster, sending it sliding a short distance before coming to a stop at Nisi's feet. Without hesitation, Nisi grabbed the shotgun and fired directly at the monster's head, killing it instantly.
"Ugh..." Rettvik muttered from the driver's seat, then awkwardly turned off the engine and climbed down from the truck. "Uh, I didn't mean to. Are you all okay?"
"You missed all the fun!" Tenuk said, clicking his tongue. "Where did you run off to?"
"It was you who left me behind. I did my best to get here..." Rettvik sighed. "Excuse me, what are these terrible things?"
Sasalin answered Rettvik's question; he had already gotten up. He was covered in wounds and scratches, looking a bit dazed, but his injuries didn't seem serious.
"You killed the Corruptor! Those infected monsters. When the Corruption attacked your gods, these creatures were left here."
"You mean... we... helped kill the terrible monster god?" Tenuk stammered.
"Yes, that's right. There might be more Corruptors. But I can't shoot them in the head. I don't have a gun. And it's not fair, two against one, right?" Sasalin walked up to Kayer and patted his head. "Thank you, little guy. You reminded me of my old friend Arcadine. Just you aren't as ruthless or as powerful in destroying the universe as he was."
"Uh... thanks... I guess..." Kayer shrugged. "So, uh, did we finish the mission?"
Nisi shrugged, picked up her camera, and took a few pictures of the monsters she was certain were dead. Then she pulled out her favorite dagger—the exquisite Reaper Dagger—and began cutting off one of the monster's horns, then the other. However, the moment Nisi finished cutting, the monsters suddenly started to combust, quickly turning into a pile of ashes. The horns Nisi had cut off also turned to ash.
“Well... I guess it's a mixed blessing..." Nisi sighed. "At least I still have the photos, right?"
